# claude-deployable — sandbox-native git config.
#
# Copy this file to .env at the repo root and `chmod 600` it.  The .env
# is gitignored; it must never be committed.  The agent sources this
# file at the start of every commit/push (see AGENTS.md and the
# ship-a-change skill).
#
# Why at the repo root?  The Cowork sandbox mounts the working tree and
# the agent runs `git` directly inside the sandbox.  Sourcing a file
# next to the code is one less path the agent has to know about.  The
# tradeoff — that the sandbox can read the PAT — is acknowledged in
# PLAN.md's security section.

# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# GitHub fine-grained PAT used to push commits.
#
# Required scopes (Repository permissions):
#   * Contents: Read and write   (push commits)
#   * Metadata: Read-only        (always required)
#
# Repository access: limit to this single repo.  A leaked token must
# not be able to reach other repos.
#
# Recommended expiration: 90 days.  An un-rotated token then surfaces
# as an auth failure rather than a silent risk.
#
# CI log reads (M3) use a SEPARATE actions:read PAT held on the VPS.
# Do NOT add actions:read to this token.
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
GH_PAT=github_pat_REPLACE_ME

# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# GitHub repo coordinates.  Used to construct the push URL:
#   https://oauth2:$GH_PAT@github.com/$GITHUB_OWNER/$GITHUB_REPO.git
# and (in M3) the /ci/runs?head_sha=... query string on the VPS agent.
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
GITHUB_OWNER=your-github-username-or-org
GITHUB_REPO=your-repo-name

# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Commit identity.  Set as GIT_AUTHOR_*/GIT_COMMITTER_* per-commit on
# every bash invocation that creates a commit (see AGENTS.md).  The
# user's global git config is never modified.
#
# Use a noreply email so the commits don't accidentally route mail
# anywhere, and so they're easy to grep for in `git log`.
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
CLAUDE_AGENT_NAME=claude-agent
CLAUDE_AGENT_EMAIL=claude-agent@users.noreply.github.com
